Problem Statement for "TrianglePath"

Problem Statement

Given is a right triangle. The three vertices of the triangle are at (0, 0), (Xmax,0), and (0, Ymax).

Also given is a collection of N (not necessarily distinct) points that all lie inside or on the boundary of the triangle. Points are numbered 0 through N-1, with point i having coordinates (X[i], Y[i]).

Your task is to construct a polyline with the following properties.

  • The polyline visits each of the given points exactly once.
  • The sum of squares of lengths of the segments of the polyline must not exceed Xmax^2 + Ymax^2.

Return a permutation of 0 through N-1 that corresponds to one possible order in which the polyline should visit the N points. Any valid solution will be accepted If there is no solution, return an empty int[] instead.

The input is generated pseudorandomly as follows: 

X = Xprefix
Y = Yprefix
state = seed
while length(X) &lt; N:
    state = (state * 1103515245 + 12345) modulo 2^31
    xnew = state modulo (Xmax + 1)
    state = (state * 1103515245 + 12345) modulo 2^31
    ynew = state modulo (Ymax + 1)
    if point (xnew, ynew) lies inside the triangle or on its boundary:
        X.append(xnew)
        Y.append(ynew)

Definition

Class:
TrianglePath
Method:
construct
Parameters:
int, int, int, int[], int[], int
Returns:
int[]
Method signature:
int[] construct(int N, int Xmax, int Ymax, int[] Xprefix, int[] Yprefix, int seed)
(be sure your method is public)

Notes

  • Note that one of the constraints implies that the triangle cannot be long and narrow, so there should not be any too-degenerate test cases.

Constraints

  • N will be between 1 and 3000, inclusive.
  • Xmax will be between 3 and 10^6, inclusive.
  • Ymax will be between 3 and 10^6, inclusive.
  • 20*Xmax >= Ymax and 20*Ymax >= Xmax.
  • Xprefix will have between 0 and min(N,500) elements.
  • Yprefix will have the same number of elements as Xprefix.
  • Each point (Xprefix[i], Yprefix[i]) will lie inside the triangle or on its boundary.
  • seed will be between 0 and 2^31 - 1, inclusive.

Examples

  1. 3

    40

    30

    {0, 40, 0}

    {0, 0, 30}

    47

    Returns: {2, 0, 1 }

    The three points are in the corners of the triangle. We can visit them in the order {1, 0, 2}. If we do so, the first segment of the polyline has length 40 and the second segment has length 30. This exactly satisfies the constraints, as 40^2 + 30^2 = 40^2 + 30^2. The reverse order {2, 0, 1} is also a valid solution, but the other four permutations are not. For example, if we visit the points in order {0, 1, 2}, the sum of squares of polyline segment lengths will be 40^2 + 50^2, which is too big.

    7

    7

    {5, 2, 4, 1, 3}

    {1, 4, 2, 5, 3}

    47

    Returns: {3, 1, 4, 2, 0 }

    54321

    12345

    {47, 47, 47}

    {47, 47, 47}

    47474747

    Returns: {0, 1, 2 }

    12

    14

    {4, 7}

    {7, 4}

    1

    Returns: {6, 5, 0, 8, 9, 3, 4, 7, 1, 2 }

    The arrays X and Y you are supposed to obtain look as follows: X = {4, 7, 9, 0, 0, 1, 2, 5, 5, 4, }; Y = {7, 4, 0, 1, 0, 7, 11, 4, 5, 5, };
